subsection.p:
As a first step in our goal of exploring the concept of transition matrix,
we re-familiarized ourselves with coordinate vectors
and reminded ourselves of their linearity properties:

	\rmatrixOf{\uvec{v} + \uvec{w}}{B} \amp = \rmatrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} + \rmatrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B} \text{,}
	\amp
	\rmatrixOf{k \uvec{v}}{B} \amp = k \rmatrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} \text{.}

To see how this can be done with a matrix,
let's switch to coordinate vectors as column vectors.
Just as in
,
we can use linearity property

applied to

to obtain an expression for the new coordinate vector \matrixOf{w}{B'}
as a linear combination in \R^n of coordinate vectors:

	\matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B'}
	= k_1 \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_1}{B'}
	+ k_2  \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_2}{B'}
	+ \dotsc
	+ k_n \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_n}{B'}.

Now, the pattern of

tells us that for every matrix P of appropriate size to multiply against the column vector \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B},
the product  P \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B}  can be expressed as

	P \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B}
	= P \begin{bmatrix} k_1 \\ k_2 \\ \vdots \\ k_n \end{bmatrix}
	= k_1 \uvec{p}_1 + k_2 \uvec{p}_2 + \dotsb + k_n \uvec{p}_n,

where the \uvec{p}_j are the columns of P.
Combining

with

gives us a way to use matrix multiplication to convert coordinate vector
\matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B} into \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B'}:
if we take P to be the matrix whose columns are the coordinate vectors relative to \basisfont{B}' of the basis vectors of \basisfont{B},

	P = \begin{bmatrix}
		| \amp | \amp | \\
		\matrixOf{\uvec{u}_1}{B'} \amp \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_1}{B'} \amp \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_1}{B'} \\
		| \amp | \amp |
	\end{bmatrix}
,
then

	P \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B}
	= k_1 \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_1}{B'} + k_2 \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_2}{B'} + \dotsb + k_n \matrixOf{\uvec{u}_n}{B'}
	= \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B'}
.
We call the special matrix P defined in

the transition matrix from basis \basisfont{B} to basis \basisfont{B}',
and write \ucobmtrx{B}{B'} to denote it.

paragraphs.p:
Since transition matrices with the standard basis as the new basis are easy to produce,
we can use the standard basis as an intermediate in a chain of basis changes to obtain any transition matrix \ucobmtrx{B}{B'} for bases of \R^n.
Using what we learned in
,
we can write

	\ucobmtrx{B}{B'}
	= \ucobmtrx{S}{B'} \ucobmtrx{B}{S}
	= \uinvcobmtrx{B'}{S} \ucobmtrx{B}{S}
,
and so we can compute \ucobmtrx{B}{B'} from the easy-to-produce transition matrices \ucobmtrx{B}{S} and \ucobmtrx{B'}{S}.
